    {
      "id": "ed8fd798a9a29706cd804bf1ac9b6e7d9568cf11",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-02 20:48:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNo comment about the patch, but I don't see how the test makes sense. The \"date\" command will complete before \"rm\" even starts, so there is no race condition being tested. Should the \"date\" execution be moved into the background?\n\nUsually for tests like this, running \"sleep\" or \"yes\" is better, since the binary can run for an arbitrary time.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "81359fc7c7154d42e7b087309ca2270e7dce3bd6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-03-02 21:45:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Andreas,\n\nActually the test case in sanity.sh is for LU-687 where it used to crash kernel if a page is truncated after releasing page lock in vvp_io_fault_start(). See OBD_FAIL_LLITE_FAULT_TRUNC_RACE handling in vvp_io.c for details. I also used ll_invalidate_page() there to produce the race condition and also that page may be still dirty. However, since that is used only for test, so I make a compromise to write date program in sync mode, instead of calling write_one_page to make it undirty.\n\nSorry for confusion.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
